In this article, the author discusses the steps being taken to achieve equal justice in the criminal justice system in America. The author announces the commuting of sentences for 11 individuals serving disproportionately long sentences for non-violent drug offenses. Additionally, a Proclamation is being issued to pardon additional offenses of simple possession and use of marijuana under federal and D.C. law. The author emphasizes that criminal records for marijuana use and possession have created barriers to employment, housing, and education, and that it is time to rectify these injustices. The author urges governors to take similar actions at the state level and highlights the efforts being made to review clemency petitions and implement reforms that promote equal justice, address racial disparities, ensure public safety, and improve the wellbeing of all Americans.